(10182, 20558, 'faq_4_answer', 'Sentek provides the most effective method for measuring soil moisture, and has been the basis for impressive improvements in irrigation mangement strategies.\r\n\r\nWhen numerical measures of soil water are recorded using continuous monitoring profiling probes – the data set allows analysis to determine not only what the soil moisture levels are, but what is causing them to change.\r\n\r\nAt the surface level, a rainfall gauge can help distinguish between rain and irrigation applications, but only a soil moisture probe can show you how much of that rain has moved through the soil to the roots of the crop.\r\n\r\nWhere rising water tables are increasing soil moisture, it can be easily identified using <a href=\"https://sentektechnologies.com/products/soil-data-probes/\">profiling probes</a>, as it will start from the lower sensors.\r\n\r\nBy using continuous data rather than occasional readings, <a href=\"http://localhost/sentek/products/advanced-software/irrimax-desktop/\">IrriMAX</a> software allows the user to build pictures of changes at any depth in the root zone.  Water uptake by the plant at different depths can clearly be seen – and measured.   Further insights include calculation of water loss, that is water that is draining past the root zone and is wasted.\r\n\r\nOver a growing season profiling probes such as <a href=\"http://localhost/sentek/products/soil-data-probes/enviroscan/\">EnviroSCAN</a> and <a href=\"http://localhost/sentek/products/soil-data-probes/drill-drop/\">Drill &amp; Drop</a> provide valuable information regarding crop growth stages, so that  intelligent decisions regarding irrigation scheduling and fertilizer applications can me made.\r\n\r\nIrriMAX has been developed by experienced soil water specialists for display of and understanding soil water and salinity dynamics. It is a powerful tool to graphically relate soil water and salinity data to the ever changing soil water plant atmosphere continuum, providing knowledge and insights. Graphical interpretation can then be readily converted to numerical analysis for final validation of irrigation scheduling results.'),
(10183, 20558, '_faq_4_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10184, 20558, 'faq', '5'),
(10185, 20558, '_faq', 'field_60090f3b7e25e'),
(10186, 20533, 'faq_0_question', 'HOW DO THE SENSORS MEASURE SOIL MOISTURE?'),
(10187, 20533, '_faq_0_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10188, 20533, 'faq_0_answer', 'Sentek sensors measure soil moisture by emitting an electric field from each sensor in the soil. The frequency of this electric field changes in response to the soil’s dielectric properties, providing measurements that are calibrated into volumetric water content.\r\n\r\nEach sensor may be programmed with the Sentek default calibration or a user defined calibration derived from a wide range of soil types to suit any application.'),
(10189, 20533, '_faq_0_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10190, 20533, 'faq_1_question', 'WHAT UNITS OF SOIL MOISTURE IS MY PROBE MEASURING?'),
(10191, 20533, '_faq_1_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10192, 20533, 'faq_1_answer', 'The raw data measured by your probe is converted via a calibration equation into volumetric soil water content. This is expressed as the volume of water per unit bulk volume of soil i.e. 1 mm = 1 mm height per square meter soil area = 1 litre.\r\n\r\nIf one sensor reads 1 mm, that means there is 1mm of water content in a 100mm thick soil slice on a volume basis. For that layer (and only that layer), this amounts to a volumetric soil water content of 1%.'),
(10193, 20533, '_faq_1_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10194, 20533, 'faq_2_question', 'CAN I USE SENTEK PROBES IN SEASONALLY FROZEN SOILS AND PERMAFROST?'),
(10195, 20533, '_faq_2_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10196, 20533, 'faq_2_answer', 'Our probes are configured to operate at temperatures between -30°C and 85°C. While measuring frozen soil is possible, the dielectric properties of ice are significantly lower than water. Therefore measuring permafrost will yield low soil water content.'),
(10197, 20533, '_faq_2_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10198, 20533, 'faq_3_question', 'WHAT COULD BE THE CAUSE OF WATER ENTRY INTO MY ACCESS TUBE, AND HOW DO I REMOVE IT?'),
(10199, 20533, '_faq_3_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10200, 20533, 'faq_3_answer', 'Some possible sources of water entry are a cracked access tube, or a broken/damaged seal in the bottom stopper or top cap. Pooled water inside the access tube can be removed with a water bailer. Next, use a clean rag attached to a pole to dry the inside of the tube, followed by another rag soaked in methylated spirits to clean the tube prior to reinserting your probe.'),
(10201, 20533, '_faq_3_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10202, 20533, 'faq_4_question', 'WHAT SENSOR DEPTHS DO I NEED?'),
(10203, 20533, '_faq_4_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10204, 20533, 'faq_4_answer', 'Sensor depths are usually determined by gathering site information about:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Root zone depth</li>\r\n 	<li>Soil profiles</li>\r\n 	<li>Water tables</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGenerally speaking for Vegetable crops we recommend a 60cm probe length, and 90cm to 120cm for Trees and Vines.'),
(10205, 20533, '_faq_4_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10206, 20533, 'faq_5_question', 'DOES MY PROBE NEED CALIBRATION?'),
(10207, 20533, '_faq_5_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10208, 20533, 'faq_5_answer', 'In commercial operations, we recommend our factory default calibrations for sensors measuring relative changes in soil water dynamics. In applications where absolute volumetric soil water content is required, soil specific calibration of your probe is essential.\r\n\r\nMore information on how to calibrate Sentek probes can be found in the <a href=\"https://sentektechnologies.com/download/moisture-calibration-manual/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Calibration Manual</a>.'),
(10209, 20533, '_faq_5_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10210, 20533, 'faq_6_question', 'WHY IS MY DIVINER 2000 FAILING TO SCAN?'),
(10211, 20533, '_faq_6_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10212, 20533, 'faq_6_answer', 'A failed scan commonly occurs when the probe length is shorter than the depth of the profile. Verify that the soil profile is correct, and ensure the full depth of the profile is reached during the scan. If problem persists, check the condition of the probe cap or the cable connector for damage.'),
(10213, 20533, '_faq_6_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10214, 20533, 'faq_7_question', 'HOW OFTEN SHOULD I REPLACE THE SILICA GEL BAGS IN MY SENTEK EQUIPMENT?'),
(10215, 20533, '_faq_7_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10216, 20533, 'faq_7_answer', 'We recommend changing your silica gel bags every 12 months, depending on environmental conditions, or as soon as the crystals inside the bag turn pink. This change of colour indicates no more moisture can be absorbed by the bag and components are at risk of damage.'),
(10217, 20533, '_faq_7_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10218, 20533, 'faq_8_question', 'HOW DOES ENVIROSCAN WORK?'),
(10219, 20533, '_faq_8_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10220, 20533, 'faq_8_answer', 'Each probe is fitted with multiple sensors located at a range of depths, these can be customized and changed as needed.  The probe rod is available at different lengths to suit a range of crops and monitoring situations.\r\n\r\nThe sensors utilize electrical capacitance to measure soil moisture.  The changing ration of air and water at each soil depth can be measured very quickly and accurately.\r\n\r\nThe sensor readings are converted to soil moisture using a calibration equation that takes into account the varying soil types.\r\n\r\nA solar or battery powered logging system is connected by cable to the probes at each monitoring site.  Data can be logged at intervals as short as every one minute, and is downloaded or cloud uploaded to a computer or phone for display.'),
(10221, 20533, '_faq_8_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
(10222, 20533, 'faq_9_question', 'HOW DO I INSTALL A DRILL & DROP PROBE?'),
(10223, 20533, '_faq_9_question', 'field_60090f757e25f'),
(10224, 20533, 'faq_9_answer', 'Use the matching Sentek auger (e.g. 30cm auger for a 30cm probe) and the installation tripod. This ensures a tapered pilot hole that is the exact shape of the probe.\r\n\r\nAllowing fast and easy insertion of the probe into undisturbed soil profile, no slurry required!\r\n\r\nWatch the video <a href=\"https://youtu.be/fasI3fnNE4Y\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">here</a>.'),
(10225, 20533, '_faq_9_answer', 'field_60090f7f7e260'),
